# Data Lake Operational Metrics as Registry+Spec \- Design

This document outlines the design for Polaris to serve as a collaborative operational metrics registry for Data Lake tables. In this approach, Polaris defines specifications for external services to submit and retrieve operational metric values, similar to how Policies are defined: their specification is stored in Polaris while implementation is delegated to query engines and external systems.

## Overview

Rather than only computing metrics internally, Polaris acts as a centralized registry where:

1. **Polaris** defines the list of operational metrics that can be computed, submitted by and served to external services  
2. **Polaris** collects and maintain some Iceberg operational metrics based on snapshot summaries and deletes them when the associated tables are deleted  
3. **Service administrators** plug their own metric external computation method (e.g. leveraging query engines, maintenance systems, …)  
4. **Service administrators** grant metrics Read and Write permissions to external services via RBAC  
5. **Polaris** validates, stores, and serves metrics through an HTTP API  
6. **Service administrators** plug their preferred database for metrics storage, via specific extension points

This collaborative design allows Polaris to centralize Data Lake Operational Metrics while leveraging the distributed computing power of external services in the Data Lake ecosystem.

## Operational Metrics System

![][image1]

### RBAC

Similar to POLICY\_READ and POLICY\_WRITE, new roles must be defined to prevent unauthorized actors from reading and writing metrics:

1. OPERATIONAL\_METRICS\_WRITE \- Permission to submit operational metrics  
2. OPERATIONAL\_METRICS\_READ \- Permission to retrieve operational metrics

Much like other privileges, those can be granted on a catalog, a namespace or a table.

### Registry

The registry contains the list of supported operational metrics.  It defines the name and type of metrics that can be computed, pushed to and fetched from Polaris by external services and query engines.

The list of supported metrics is statically defined.  It may become dynamic in a subsequent phase.

### API

In order to distinguish the Operational Metrics API from the Iceberg REST API , while maintaining consistency, a new OpenAPI definition is created.  All Operational Metrics endpoints are located under `/api/operational-metrics`.  See the “API” document tab for the list of API endpoints.

### SPI

A Service Provider Interface is defined to allow service administrators to use their preferred database for metrics storage and retrieval.  This flexibility enables administrators to decide whether they want to keep all historical values in a time-series database, use custom retention policy, etc…

The interface contains:

* A method to store new values for given metrics, including information about the associated table, its namespace and its realm  
* A method to fetch the latest values of all metrics of a given table  
* A method to fetch the latest value of a single metric of a given table  
* A method to delete the metrics of a given table

E.g. interface could look like:

public interface OperationalMetricsPersistence {  
  void storeMetrics(  
    @Nonnull PolarisCallContext callContext,  
    @Nonnull PolarisEntityId tableId,  
    @Nonnull Map\<String, MetricValueWithMetadata\> metrics);

  @Nonnull  
  Map\<String, MetricValueWithMetadata\> getAllMetrics(  
    @Nonnull PolarisCallContext callContext, @Nonnull PolarisEntityId tableId);

  @Nullable  
  MetricValueWithMetadata getSingleMetric(  
      @Nonnull PolarisCallContext callContext,  
      @Nonnull PolarisEntityId tableId,  
      @Nonnull String metricName);

  @Nonnull  
  Map\<String, MetricValueWithMetadata\> deleteAllMetrics(  
    @Nonnull PolarisCallContext callContext, @Nonnull PolarisEntityId tableId);  
}

Note that the example given includes a PolarisCallContext instance to all method parameters.  This may change depending on the outcome of [PR \#2556](https://github.com/apache/polaris/pull/2556/files).

### Initial list of operational metrics

During the first stage we will implement the metrics that are available in the snapshot summary of the Iceberg metadata.json: [https://github.com/apache/iceberg/blob/96a588038a8029cf2d5cf3487682d1ecdce63275/core/src/main/java/org/apache/iceberg/SnapshotSummary.java\#L31-L31](https://github.com/apache/iceberg/blob/96a588038a8029cf2d5cf3487682d1ecdce63275/core/src/main/java/org/apache/iceberg/SnapshotSummary.java#L31-L31)

The following metrics available there look could be used:

- total-files-size  
- total-data-files  
- total-delete-files  
- total-position-deletes  
- total-equality-deletes  
- total-records

Note: snapshot summary may optionally contain partition summary metrics. For now it does not seem plausible for us to use them to compute partition-level metrics: they only contain diff numbers for actually changed partitions, and are not a reliable source for incremental calculations since there is a limit for number of partitions in a snapshot summary.  There are other concerns, e.g. it is not populated by default and requires explicit setup.  Also, if partitions are indexed using sensitive data, we might need to store PII in metrics persistence for those incremental calculations.  But we should keep an eye for changes in Iceberg specs that could make them usable for our case.

On the second stage we will support metrics that require external compute:

- data-file-size-stats \- Data file size distribution statistics  
- partition-count \- Number of distinct partitions  
- partition-size-stats \- Partition size distribution statistics

Additional metrics can be added in subsequent phases if users request them. 

## Storage

Storage implementations can be configured by instructing Polaris to use a specific SPI implementation.  Database specifics (types, schemas) are enforced by each SPI implementation.

The Metrics database is assumed to be secured and trusted.  I.e. It is the administrators’ responsibility to ensure that metrics are only accessible to the appropriate services.

Out of the box, Polaris comes with two SPI implementations described below.

### No-Op

A No-Op SPI implementation is bundled with Polaris and does not contain any specific code.  In other words, when it is used, metrics are not persisted to a database.  Similarly, any read query results in an empty result being returned.

By default, this SPI is used by Polaris.  In other words, metrics support is effectively disabled by default.

### Postgres

A reference implementation of the SPI for JDBC storage is also provided, together with a database schema for the Polaris Postgres database.

Possible DB schema for Postgres implementation:

CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS operational\_metrics (  
    realm\_id TEXT NOT NULL,  
    catalog\_id BIGINT NOT NULL,  
    table\_id BIGINT NOT NULL,  
    metric\_name TEXT NOT NULL,

    metric\_data JSONB NOT NULL,

    PRIMARY KEY (realm\_id, table\_id, metric\_name)  
);

## Data Cleanup / Retention Policy

Data cleanup is dependent on each SPI implementation.  Polaris issues an SPI call after a table is dropped so that all associated metrics can be deleted too.

### Postgres

The reference implementation of the SPI for JDBC storage only stores the latest metric values.  It does not store historical data.  As a result, the data cleanup logic is straightforward: metrics can only be deleted when a table is dropped.  Otherwise, they should be kept.

### Other SPI implementations

Other SPI implementations can follow the example of the JDBC reference implementation for data cleanup.

For implementations that keep historical data, custom retention policies must be defined.  Retention policies are outside of the SPI scope.  It is the administrators’ responsibility to implement proper retention policies.

## Deployment model

The Operational Metrics system is integrated in the Polaris server.  Its API is deployed alongside other Polaris API (catalog, management) in the same Quarkus runtime.

## Data representation

### Point metrics

Certain metrics contain a single value (e.g. total number of files in a table, total number of partitions, …).  For those metrics, the storage format as well as the API response format is trivial: it is composed of the metric name and its value, as well as the timestamp of the last metric update.

### Histograms

Histograms inherently require more than a single data point.  For those metrics, the storage format consists in a series of percentiles, as well as the arithmetic average, the standard deviation and the total sum of all values.  The expected percentiles are: the minimum (p0), the 10th, 25th, median, 75th, 90th and 99th percentiles (p10, p25, p50, p75, p90, p99) as well as outliers percentiles and maximum value (p99.9, p99.99 and p100).

## Non-Iceberg tables

The operational metrics component may be able to compute a subset of metrics for non-iceberg tables.  Typically, for Generic Tables that are partitioned, it could be possible to compute the total number of partitions and the partition sizes statistics.  The same could also apply for Table Sources, should the proposal be accepted.
